'''David Montgomery''' is the part-owner, general partner, [[President#Non-governmental_presidents|president]], and [[chief executive officer]] of the [[Philadelphia Phillies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/team/front_office.jsp?c_id=phi|title=Front Office|publisher=Philadelphia Phillies|accessdate=August 19, 2008}}</ref> 

==Early life and education==
As a child, Montgomery attended Phillies games at [[Connie Mack Stadium]] with future governor [[Ed Rendell]], where he recalled "<nowiki>[trying]</nowiki> to eat all the food that $5 could buy... as they shared their thoughts with the players".<ref name="nytimes"/> Before attending college, Montgomery worked as a diaper delivery boy and a high school [[baseball]] coach. <ref name="upenn"/> As an [[undergraduate]], Montgomery attended the [[University of Pennsylvania]], where he was first a [[liberal arts]] major,<ref name="upenn">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypennsylvanian.com/node/27164|title=Phillies CEO gives life lesson|last=Silverman|first=Rachel|date=October 2, 2002|work=The Daily Pennsylvanian|accessdate=April 22, 2010}}</ref> and then a [[history]] major.<ref name="nytimes">{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/22/sports/baseball/22baseball.html?_r=2|title=Phillies<U+2019> President Took Path From Upper Deck to the Owner<U+2019>s Box|last=Kepner|first=Tyler|date=October 21, 2008|work=The New York Times|page=1|accessdate=April 22, 2010}}</ref> He also attended the [[Wharton Business School]] as a graduate student, graduating in 1970.<ref name="wharton">{{cite web|url=http://media.www.whartonjournal.com/media/storage/paper201/news/2003/02/17/News/Batting.Practice.In.Huntsman.David.Montgomery.Wg70-371106.shtml|title=Batting practice in Huntsman: David Montgomery WG'70|date=February 17, 2003|work=The Wharton Journal|page=1|accessdate=April 22, 2010}}</ref> During his tenure at Wharton, he also coached the [[linemen]] for the varsity [[American football|football]] team at [[Germantown Academy]].<ref name="nytimes"/>

==Baseball career==
After interviewing for positions with [[Scott Paper]] and [[Quaker Oats]] and being encouraged by Rendell to apply for a job with the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], Montgomery reached out to former Phillies ace [[Robin Roberts (baseball)|Robin Roberts]], whose son he coached at Germantown, about a job with the baseball club.<ref name="nytimes"/> Montgomery was hired as a member of the Phillies' sales department in 1971,<ref name="wharton"/> becoming director of sales and marketing in the mid-1970s and the head of the business department by 1980.<ref name="nytimes"/> During the early 1970s, he was also the team's scoreboard operator.<ref name="nytimes"/>

Montgomery, along with co-owner [[Bill Giles (baseball)|Bill Giles]], purchased the team in 1981 for $30,000,000;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/finance/lists/33/2005/LIR.jhtml?passListId=33&passYear=2005&passListType=Misc&uniqueId=335119&datatype=Misc|title=MLB Team Valuations 2005|last=Ozanian|first=Michael K., ed|date=April 7, 2005|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=August 19, 2008}}</ref> Giles, the primary owner, named Montgomery the executive vice president of the team.<ref name="nytimes2">{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/22/sports/baseball/22baseball.html?pagewanted=2&_r=2|title=Phillies<U+2019> President Took Path From Upper Deck to the Owner<U+2019>s Box|last=Kepner|first=Tyler|date=October 21, 2008|work=The New York Times|page=2|accessdate=April 22, 2010}}</ref> In 1997, when Giles left the team presidency to become the chairman and focus on winning a new stadium for the team,<ref>{{cite book|last=Jordan|first=David M.|title=Occasional glory: the history of the Philadelphia Phillies|publisher=McFarland|date=2002|page=245|isbn=0786412607|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=3QB66gphVloC&pg=PA245&dq=david+montgomery+phillies&hl=en&ei=cmDPS7vuDYOKlweF6MmgCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CFUQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=david%20montgomery%20phillies&f=false}}</ref> he recommended Montgomery to replace him as team president.<ref name="nytimes2"/> In so doing, Montgomery became the first native of Philadelphia to run the club in over 60 years.<ref>{{cite book|last=Westcott|first=Rich|title=Philadelphia Phillies Past & Present|publisher=MBI Publishing Company|date=2010|page=36|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=K_e8KWxmo_kC&pg=PA36&dq=david+montgomery+phillies&hl=en&ei=cmDPS7vuDYOKlweF6MmgCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CEEQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=david%20montgomery%20phillies&f=false|isbn=0760337845}}</ref> One of his focuses with the team has been brand development, evidenced by the team's commitment to signing successful players to long-term contracts prior to the opening of [[Citizens Bank Park]] in 2004.<ref name="nytimes2"/><ref name="wharton2">{{cite web|url=http://media.www.whartonjournal.com/media/storage/paper201/news/2003/02/17/News/Batting.Practice.In.Huntsman.David.Montgomery.Wg70-371106-page2.shtml|title=Batting practice in Huntsman: David Montgomery WG'70|date=February 17, 2003|work=The Wharton Journal|page=2|accessdate=April 22, 2010}}</ref>

==Outside baseball==
Montgomery has been a trustee of the University of Pennsylvania, served community action groups, and been a member of Major League Baseball Enterprise's board of directors.<ref name="upenn"/>

